{"key":"post-10188539","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10188539</id>\n<content>If you vacuum seal the bags, you won't be able to insert a thermometer into the center of the substrate, thus you won't know when you've reached pasteurization temp.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I pasteurize in filter patch bags all the time, but leave them unsealed.&amp;nbsp; Your cooler idea won't work.&amp;nbsp; You want the center of your substrate &lt;i&gt;within&lt;/i&gt; the bags to be at 140F to 160F for an hour.&amp;nbsp; If you had them in 160F water, I doubt they'd reach that temp even if you left them for 12 hours.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Load your bags and put them in large pots of water on the stove.&amp;nbsp; Use your stove burner to regulate the temp in the center of the bags, and keep them in the range stated above.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10188555</next>\n<prev>10187885</prev>\n<first>10100821</first>\n<last>11768477</last>\n<when>1240062616</when>\n<utime>04/18/09 04:50 PM</utime>\n</post>"}